tory of the Metropolitan Railway|publisher=Lamplight Publications|location=Witney|year=2003|volume=1|isbn=1-899246-07-X}}\n*{{cite book|last=Simpson|first=Bill|title=A History of the Metropolitan Railway|publisher=Lamplight Publications|location=Witney|year=2004|volume=2|isbn=1-899246-08-8}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Brill Tramway}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110611063724/http://www.britishpathe.com/record.php?id=6464 Newsreel footage of the last day of operations] at [[Path\u00e9|British Path\u00e9]]\n*[http://www.bucksrailcentre.org/ Buckinghamshire Railway Centre], based at Quainton Road station\n\n{{Metropolitan line navbox}}\n{{London Underground rolling stock}}\n{{Transport in Buckinghamshire}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n[[Category:Brill Tramway]]\n[[Category:Predecessor companies of the London Underground]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1871]]\n[[Category:Railway lines closed in 1935]]\n[[Category:Horse-drawn railways]]\n", "name_user": "RioVerde", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWaddesdon Manor:Minor edit.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brill_Tramway"}
{"title_page": "WHVN", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = WHVN\n| image            = \n| city             = [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]\n| area             = Charlotte\n| branding         = \n| slogan           = Heaven Radio\n| airdate          = [[1929 in radio|1929]]\n| last airdate     = March 31, [[2020 in radio|2020]]\n| frequency        = 1240 [[kHz]]\n| power            = 1,000 [[Watt]]s (day and night)\n| erp              = \n| haat             =\n| class            = C\n| facility_id      = 72331\n| coordinates      = {{coord|35|12|00|N|80|48|39|W}}\n| callsign_meaning = '''H'''ea'''V'''e'''N'''\n| former_callsigns = WRBU (1929-1930s)<br>WSOC (1930s-early 1960s)<br>WIST (early 1960s-1983)\n| former_frequencies = 1210 (1929-early 1960s)\n| owner            = WHVN Inc.\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  = [[WCGC]], [[WAVO]], [[WOLS]]\n| webcast          = \n| website          = [http://www.heavenradio.org www.heavenradio.org]\n| affiliations     = \n}}\n\n'''WHVN''' (1240 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) was a religious [[radio station]] licensed to [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte, North Carolina, United States]].  The station was owned by WHVN Inc.  The station was simulcast onto [[WAVO]] at 1150 AM and was also heard on 104.3 FM W282BP.\n\nWHVN was licensed by the [[U.S. Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) for digital [[HD Radio|HD]] operation.<ref>http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/sta_det.pl?Facility_id=27218</ref><ref>http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/sta_det.pl?Facility_id=72331</ref><ref>http://www.hdradio.com/stations/North+Carolina-NC/Charlotte-Gastonia-Rock+Hill-14</ref>\n\nWHVN was scheduled to cease operations on March 31, 2020.<ref name=\"Heaven Radio\"/>\n\n==History==\n===Early Years===\nThe station that would become WHVN on the 1240 frequency in Charlotte began operations in 1929 in [[Gastonia, North Carolina]] on 1210&nbsp;kHz with the call letters WRBU.  According to a 1930 [[Federal Radio Commission]] listing, the station had a power of 100 watts and was licensed to the \"A. J. Kirby Music Company\".  Sometime in the 1930s the station's city of license was changed to Charlotte and the call sign was changed to WSOC, supposedly meaning \"We Serve Our City\".  The 1941 [[North American Regional Broadcasting Agreement]] (NARBA) mandated a change in frequency to 1240&nbsp;kHz. In the late 1950s, most stations on \"Class IV\" (local) frequencies were allowed to increase their daytime power to 1,000 watts, and WSOC increased their daytime power as well.  Also in the 1950s the owners of WSOC brought to the air [[WSOC-FM]] at 103.7&nbsp;MHz, and [[WSOC-TV]] on [[VHF]] channel 9.\n\n===Top 40 era===\nOn September 2, 1960, Cox Broadcasting Company, then-owners of WSOC, traded frequencies with WIST at [[WYFQ|930&nbsp;kHz]]<ref>''The Charlotte News'', Sept. 1, 1960, p. 28.</ref>  Under the ownership of [[Cosmos Broadcasting]] and later [[Henderson Belk]] the station gained the WIST legacy of the first true [[Top 40]] station in Charlotte, and by the end of the decade had pioneered the [[Progressive rock]] format in Charlotte as \"The Amazing AM\", but changes were in the works.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}  In 1972, the Progressive Rock format was shifted to [[WNKS|WIST-FM]] at 95.1&nbsp;MHz, and their calls were changed to WRNA.<ref>http://www.thatwasradio.com/ways.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507041637/http://www.thatwasradio.com/ways.html |date=2007-05-07 }}, Retrieved on February 28, 2008.</ref>  Belk then sold WIST(AM) to Statesville Broadcasting Company, which gained [[CBS Radio Network]] affiliation for the station and began Charlotte's first [[talk radio]] format on WIST.  Charlotte radio legend [[Jack Knight (radio host)|Jack Knight]] was hired to do the morning show.  Future [[John Boy and Billy]] sidekick [[Robert D. Raiford]] hosted one of the talk shows, and was notorious for screaming at callers.  The format was unsuccessful, and Statesville Broadcasting sold the station by the middle of the 1970s.\n\n===Adult Contemporary turned Country era===\nWIST/1240's next ownership was a partnership between former WBT ad salesman Al Munn and [[Consolidated Theater Corporation]].  Munn initially changed the format to [[Adult contemporary music]] and brought his family into the employ of the station.  Munn also attempted to operate the station as a broadcasting school, eventually separating the school functions into the \"WISTA School of Broadcasting.\"  In 1979 the Charlotte radio landscape had a major change.  Longtime AM [[country music]] leader [[WGFY|WAME]] was purchased by [[Jimmy Swaggart|Jimmy Swaggart Ministries]] and became a [[Christian radio|religious station]].  The country music format hole was quickly filled by WIST, becoming \"Live Country 1240\".  By this time the partnership between Munn and Consolidated Theaters was coming unraveled, and the theater company bought Munn out of the arrangement.\n\nIn the early 1980s, WIST gave country music its last serious attempt on the AM dial in Charlotte, becoming \"The Bright Spot.\"  The format was innovative, but most country listeners had switched to WSOC-FM and the format did not succeed.  As its last gasp, WIST tried Top 40 again in the early 1980s before signing off the air.\n\n===Switch to religious format===\nIn 1983, The station was purchased by George H. Buck, who at that time owned WHVN, which operated daytime-only at 1310&nbsp;kHz.  Originally, 1310 had been WKTC, Charlotte's first country station, before adopting a Christian format in 1971.  WHVN moved to the 1240 frequency, and sold its old frequency to Dick Tomlinson.  Tomlinson began [[WGSP (AM)|WGSP]] on 1310, which exists today as a [[Regional Mexican]] format.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}\n\nFor most of the years between 1996 and 2008, [[WAVO]] in [[Rock Hill, South Carolina]] simulcast WHVN.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Price |title=Christian Radio Tries to Offer Variety |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=1996-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Washburn |title=WAVO Moves to the Sounds of Sinatra, Ella |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=2008-07-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, WHVN's owner bought [[WCGC]] in [[Belmont, North Carolina|Belmont]].<ref>Audrey Y. Williams, \"Gastonia Employee Sues Over Radio Comments,\" ''The Charlotte Observer'', August 11, 1998.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, WHVN Inc. bought an existing permit for a [[Broadcast relay station|translator]] at 93.5 FM.<ref>http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DOC-289797A1.pdf\n</ref>  As of August 2009, the radio station uses another translator at 104.3 FM.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Washburn |title=Velvet-voiced radio host says goodbye in cutbacks  |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=2008-08-01}}</ref>\n\n===Later years and shutdown===\nIn 2014, [[WEGO (AM)|WTIX]] in [[Concord, North Carolina]] (currently WEGO) began simulcasting WHVN. This ended with the WTIX sale in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independenttribune.com/news/concord-radio-station-sold-to-catawba-foundation-in-salisbury/article_c2db5efc-b55f-11e5-83a9-7fa6f4408953.html|title=Concord radio station sold to Catawba Foundation in Salisbury |work=Independent Tribune |date=2016-01-07 |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wbtv.com/story/30896166/new-details-on-catawba-college-foundation-purchase-of-concord-radio-station|title=New details on Catawba College Foundation purchase of Concord radio station|last=Whisenant|first=David|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2016-01-06|accessdate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, WAVO began simulcasting WHVN again.\n\nOn February 1, 2019, The Carolina Catholic Radio Network entered into an LMA with GHB Broadcasting to operate WCGC. The majority of the programming would come from EWTN. <ref> https://www.gastongazette.com/news/20190218/1270-am-in-gaston-now-carolina-catholic-radio</ref>\n[[Image:Whvn logo.jpg|thumb|left|Final logo of WHVN]]\nOn March 30, 2020, It was anounced that WHVN will go off the air the next day. After the owner's death in 2013, a trustee was told to continue the businesses but eventually sell them in order to care for his widow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heavenradio.org|title=WHVN Charlotte|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station's farewell program was a call-in show where listeners talk about their memories. When that program ended, after a final sign-off, WHVN's transmitter was scheduled to shut down for the final time at 5:00pm, bringing a close to the 91-year history of the station. The 8 acres where the transmitter was located have been [[Rezoning|rezoned]] for developing medical offices in light of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Heaven Radio\">{{cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/185693/whvn-to-go-to-heaven/|title=WHVN To Go To Heaven|last=Venta|first=Lance|publisher=radioinsight|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|WHVN}}\n{{FM station data|W282BP}} \n\n{{Charlotte Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in the Charlotte metropolitan area|HVN]]\n[[Category:Moody Radio affiliate stations]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1929]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = WHVN\n| image            = \n| city             = [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]\n| area             = Charlotte\n| branding         = \n| slogan           = Heaven Radio\n| airdate          = [[1929 in radio|1929]]\n| last airdate     = March 31, [[2020 in radio|2020]]\n| frequency        = 1240 [[kHz]]\n| power            = 1,000 [[Watt]]s (day and night)\n| erp              = \n| haat             =\n| class            = C\n| facility_id      = 72331\n| coordinates      = {{coord|35|12|00|N|80|48|39|W}}\n| callsign_meaning = '''H'''ea'''V'''e'''N'''\n| former_callsigns = WRBU (1929-1930s)<br>WSOC (1930s-early 1960s)<br>WIST (early 1960s-1983)\n| former_frequencies = 1210 (1929-early 1960s)\n| owner            = WHVN Inc.\n| licensee         = \n| sister_stations  = [[WCGC]], [[WAVO]], [[WOLS]]\n| webcast          = \n| website          = [http://www.heavenradio.org www.heavenradio.org]\n| affiliations     = \n}}\n\n'''WHVN''' (1240 [[AM broadcasting|AM]]) was a religious [[radio station]] licensed to [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte, North Carolina, United States]].  The station was owned by WHVN Inc.  The station was simulcast onto [[WAVO]] at 1150 AM and was also heard on 104.3 FM W282BP.\n\nWHVN was licensed by the [[U.S. Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) for digital [[HD Radio|HD]] operation.<ref>http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/sta_det.pl?Facility_id=27218</ref><ref>http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/sta_det.pl?Facility_id=72331</ref><ref>http://www.hdradio.com/stations/North+Carolina-NC/Charlotte-Gastonia-Rock+Hill-14</ref>\n\nWHVN was scheduled to cease operations on March 31, 2020.<ref name=\"Heaven Radio\"/>\n\n==History==\n===Early Years===\nThe station that would become WHVN on the 1240 frequency in Charlotte began operations in 1929 in [[Gastonia, North Carolina]] on 1210&nbsp;kHz with the call letters WRBU.  According to a 1930 [[Federal Radio Commission]] listing, the station had a power of 100 watts and was licensed to the \"A. J. Kirby Music Company\".  Sometime in the 1930s the station's city of license was changed to Charlotte and the call sign was changed to WSOC, supposedly meaning \"We Serve Our City\".  The 1941 [[North American Regional Broadcasting Agreement]] (NARBA) mandated a change in frequency to 1240&nbsp;kHz. In the late 1950s, most stations on \"Class IV\" (local) frequencies were allowed to increase their daytime power to 1,000 watts, and WSOC increased their daytime power as well.  Also in the 1950s the owners of WSOC brought to the air [[WSOC-FM]] at 103.7&nbsp;MHz, and [[WSOC-TV]] on [[VHF]] channel 9.\n\n===Top 40 era===\nOn September 2, 1960, Cox Broadcasting Company, then-owners of WSOC, traded frequencies with WIST at [[WYFQ|930&nbsp;kHz]]<ref>''The Charlotte News'', Sept. 1, 1960, p. 28.</ref>  Under the ownership of [[Cosmos Broadcasting]] and later [[Henderson Belk]] the station gained the WIST legacy of the first true [[Top 40]] station in Charlotte, and by the end of the decade had pioneered the [[Progressive rock]] format in Charlotte as \"The Amazing AM\", but changes were in the works.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}  In 1972, the Progressive Rock format was shifted to [[WNKS|WIST-FM]] at 95.1&nbsp;MHz, and their calls were changed to WRNA.<ref>http://www.thatwasradio.com/ways.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070507041637/http://www.thatwasradio.com/ways.html |date=2007-05-07 }}, Retrieved on February 28, 2008.</ref>  Belk then sold WIST(AM) to Statesville Broadcasting Company, which gained [[CBS Radio Network]] affiliation for the station and began Charlotte's first [[talk radio]] format on WIST.  Charlotte radio legend [[Jack Knight (radio host)|Jack Knight]] was hired to do the morning show.  Future [[John Boy and Billy]] sidekick [[Robert D. Raiford]] hosted one of the talk shows, and was notorious for screaming at callers.  The format was unsuccessful, and Statesville Broadcasting sold the station by the middle of the 1970s.\n\n===Adult Contemporary turned Country era===\nWIST/1240's next ownership was a partnership between former WBT ad salesman Al Munn and [[Consolidated Theater Corporation]].  Munn initially changed the format to [[Adult contemporary music]] and brought his family into the employ of the station.  Munn also attempted to operate the station as a broadcasting school, eventually separating the school functions into the \"WISTA School of Broadcasting.\"  In 1979 the Charlotte radio landscape had a major change.  Longtime AM [[country music]] leader [[WGFY|WAME]] was purchased by [[Jimmy Swaggart|Jimmy Swaggart Ministries]] and became a [[Christian radio|religious station]].  The country music format hole was quickly filled by WIST, becoming \"Live Country 1240\".  By this time the partnership between Munn and Consolidated Theaters was coming unraveled, and the theater company bought Munn out of the arrangement.\n\nIn the early 1980s, WIST gave country music its last serious attempt on the AM dial in Charlotte, becoming \"The Bright Spot.\"  The format was innovative, but most country listeners had switched to WSOC-FM and the format did not succeed.  As its last gasp, WIST tried Top 40 again in the early 1980s before signing off the air.\n\n===Switch to religious format===\nIn 1983, The station was purchased by George H. Buck, who at that time owned WHVN, which operated daytime-only at 1310&nbsp;kHz.  Originally, 1310 had been WKTC, Charlotte's first country station, before adopting a Christian format in 1971.  WHVN moved to the 1240 frequency, and sold its old frequency to Dick Tomlinson.  Tomlinson began [[WGSP (AM)|WGSP]] on 1310, which exists today as a [[Regional Mexican]] format.{{Citation needed|date=September 2008}}\n\nFor most of the years between 1996 and 2008, [[WAVO]] in [[Rock Hill, South Carolina]] simulcast WHVN.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Price |title=Christian Radio Tries to Offer Variety |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=1996-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Washburn |title=WAVO Moves to the Sounds of Sinatra, Ella |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=2008-07-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, WHVN's owner bought [[WCGC]] in [[Belmont, North Carolina|Belmont]].<ref>Audrey Y. Williams, \"Gastonia Employee Sues Over Radio Comments,\" ''The Charlotte Observer'', August 11, 1998.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, WHVN Inc. bought an existing permit for a [[Broadcast relay station|translator]] at 93.5 FM.<ref>http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/edocs_public/attachmatch/DOC-289797A1.pdf\n</ref>  As of August 2009, the radio station uses another translator at 104.3 FM.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Washburn |title=Velvet-voiced radio host says goodbye in cutbacks  |work=The Charlotte Observer |date=2008-08-01}}</ref>\n\n===Later years and shutdown===\nIn 2014, [[WEGO (AM)|WTIX]] in [[Concord, North Carolina]] (currently WEGO) began simulcasting WHVN. This ended with the WTIX sale in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independenttribune.com/news/concord-radio-station-sold-to-catawba-foundation-in-salisbury/article_c2db5efc-b55f-11e5-83a9-7fa6f4408953.html|title=Concord radio station sold to Catawba Foundation in Salisbury |work=Independent Tribune |date=2016-01-07 |accessdate=2016-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wbtv.com/story/30896166/new-details-on-catawba-college-foundation-purchase-of-concord-radio-station|title=New details on Catawba College Foundation purchase of Concord radio station|last=Whisenant|first=David|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2016-01-06|accessdate=2016-01-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, WAVO began simulcasting WHVN again.\n\nOn February 1, 2019, The Carolina Catholic Radio Network entered into an LMA with GHB Broadcasting to operate WCGC. The majority of the programming would come from EWTN. <ref> https://www.gastongazette.com/news/20190218/1270-am-in-gaston-now-carolina-catholic-radio</ref>\n[[Image:Whvn logo.jpg|thumb|left|Final logo of WHVN]]\nOn March 30, 2020, It was anounced that WHVN will go off the air the next day. After the owner's death in 2013, a trustee was told to continue the businesses but eventually sell them in order to care for his widow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heavenradio.org|title=WHVN Charlotte|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> The station's farewell program was a call-in show where listeners talk about their memories. When that program ended, after a final sign-off, WHVN's transmitter was scheduled to shut down for the final time at 5:00pm, bringing a close to the 91 year history of the station. The 8 acres where the transmitter was located have been [[Rezoning|rezoned]] for developing medical offices in light of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Heaven Radio\">{{cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/185693/whvn-to-go-to-heaven/|title=WHVN To Go To Heaven|last=Venta|first=Lance|publisher=radioinsight|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|WHVN}}\n{{FM station data|W282BP}} \n\n{{Charlotte Radio}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in the Charlotte metropolitan area|HVN]]\n[[Category:Moody Radio affiliate stations]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1929]]\n", "name_user": "Stereorock", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater years and shutdown", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WHVN"}
{"title_page": "Anatole Klyosov", "text_new": "[[File:Prof Kljosov.jpg|thumb|2008 photo]]\n'''Anatole A. Klyosov''' (born 20 November 1946 in [[Chernyakhovsk]], [[Kaliningrad Oblast]] of [[Russian SFSR]])<ref name=mgu/> is a scientist who worked in the fields of physical chemistry, enzyme catalysis, and industrial biochemistry. In 1989 Klyosov immigrated to the US.  He spent most of his career developing ways to use [[enzymes]] to convert agricultural waste products into useful products \u2014 first to convert cotton waste to glucose in the USSR, and later in the US, turning paper mill waste into useful products.  He later helped found a company, and later joined it as CSO, that was founded to use enzymes to alter existing [[anticancer drug]]s via [[glycosylation]]. In 2008 he began publishing work on what he calls \"DNA genealogy\".\n\n== Career ==\nKlyosov earned Ph.D. and D.Sc. degrees in physical chemistry, and an M.S. degree in enzyme kinetics, from [[Moscow State University]].<ref name=PPpressrelease2006/>  In the late 1970s he worked at Harvard University; he was offered a contract to keep working there but the USSR government would not allow him to take it and he remained in the USSR.<ref name=Spiegel/> From 1979 to 1981 he was professor in the department of chemical enzymology at Moscow State University.<ref name=mgu>{{cite web|url=http://letopis.msu.ru/peoples/4652|title=\u041a\u043b\u0451\u0441\u043e\u0432 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 = Klyosov Anatoly Alekseyevich|website=\u041b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430|publisher=\u0410\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u041c\u0413\u0423|location=Moscow|language=ru|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6nWncHQ9L?url=http://letopis.msu.ru/peoples/4652|archive-date=2017-01-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1981 to 1990, he was professor and head of the Carbohydrates Research Laboratory at the A.N. Bach Institute of Biochemistry, USSR Academy of Sciences.<ref name=GalectinBIo>{{cite web |title=Galectin Therapeutics Advisory Board |url=http://galectintherapeutics.com/who-we-are/scientific-advisory-board/ |accessdate=16 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121003843/http://galectintherapeutics.com/who-we-are/scientific-advisory-board/ |archive-date=2014-11-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  In the winter of 1982/1983 he became the first person behind the [[Iron Curtain]] who was allowed by the government of the [[USSR]] to use the computer network that later became [[the Internet]], in order for him to represent the USSR in a conference hosted on the network; he used a computer hosted on Institute's network.<ref name=Spiegel>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/internet-pionier-kljosow-genosse-online-a-723933.html|title=Internet-Pionier Kljosow: Genosse Online|date=22 October 2010|work=SPIEGEL ONLINE|accessdate=15 October 2014}}</ref>  He said that he developed methods to use [[enzyme]]s to convert cotton plant waste products into glucose and by 1983 a [[Demonstration Plant|pilot plant]] had been built in the USSR to test these methods.<ref name=NewScientist1983>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Russians catch the nu-food bug |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XLlzpvKTIjMC&pg=PA543 |journal=New Scientist |date=26 May 1983 |page=543 }}</ref>  He was awarded top Russian prizes in science and technology field: the [[Lenin Komsomol Prize]] in 1978 and the [[USSR State Prize]] in 1984.<ref name=mgu/><ref name=arch/> In 1989 he was made a fellow of the [[World Academy of Art and Science]].<ref>{{cite web |title=World Academy of Art and Science |url=http://www.worldacademy.org/content/anatole-klyosov |access-date=2014-10-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021225651/http://www.worldacademy.org/content/anatole-klyosov |archive-date=2014-10-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2014 he became Foreign Member of the National Academy of Sciences of Georgia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Georgian National Academy of Sciences, Foreign Members |url=http://science.org.ge/newsite/?page_id=1982}}</ref>\n\nKlyosov immigrated to the US in 1989<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.kp.ru/daily/26535.7/3551840/ |title= \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0440 \u041c\u0413\u0423 \u0438 \u0413\u0430\u0440\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0432: \u0413\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0430 - \u043e\u0442\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043e\u0442 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432 \u0432\u044b \u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0451\u0442\u0435 |trans-title= Anatoly Klyosov, Professor of Moscow State University and of Harvard: Genetics Show That You Cannot Find Differences Between Russians And Ukrainians |last= Alekhina |first= Yuliya |date= 2016-05-27 |publisher= [[Komsomolskaya Pravda]] |language= ru |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160528181910/http://www.kp.ru/daily/26535.7/3551840/|archive-date=2016-05-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> after [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] came to power,<ref name=Spiegel/> and from 1990 to 1998 he was a visiting professor of biochemistry at the Center for Biochemical and Biophysical Sciences at Harvard Medical School.<ref name=GalectinBIo/>\n\nIn 1991 he started a consulting business called MIR International.<ref name=mir-summ>{{cite web |url= http://corp.sec.state.ma.us/CorpWeb/CorpSearch/CorpSummary.aspx?FEIN=043138282&SEARCH_TYPE=1 |title= Business Entity Summary for: MIR INTERNATIONAL, INC. |publisher= Massachusetts Secretary of the Commonwealth |access-date= 2016-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://corp.sec.state.ma.us/CorpWeb/CorpSearch/CorpSearchRedirector.aspx?Action=PDF&Path=CORP_DRIVE1/2016/0101/000000000/5944/201657331710_1.pdf |title= Annual report: MIR INTERNATIONAL, INC. |publisher= Massachusetts Secretary of the Commonwealth |access-date= 2016-06-22 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 2006 Klyosov worked at a subsidiary of [[Kadant]], where he applied enzymology to processing of waste products from the paper-making industry, and following advice from a friend in the plastics industry, helped create a business that used cellulose granules as filler material for plastic composite products.<ref name=PPpressrelease2006>{{cite web|title=Press Release: Pro-Pharmaceuticals Announces the Appointment of Anatole Klyosov, Ph.D., D.Sc. as Chief Scientist.|url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/Pro-Pharmaceuticals+Announces+the+Appointment+of+Anatole+Klyosov,+...-a0140816207|publisher=Pro-Pharmaceuticals via the Free Online Library|date=January 13, 2006}}</ref><ref name=PT2004>{{cite news|last1=Schut|first1=Jan H.|title=From Paper-Mill Sludge to Plastic Decking |url=http://www.ptonline.com/articles/from-paper-mill-sludge-to-plastic-decking|work=Plastics Technology|date=October 2004}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 he helped found Pro-Pharmaceuticals, a company that was formed to use enzymes to [[Glycosylation|add carbodydrates]] to existing cancer drugs to make them work better, and was caught up in scandal in 2004 when the company's investors accused its CEO of misrepresenting his role in the company.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Krasner|first1=Jeffrey|title=David Platt wants to cure cancer. Can his company avoid life support?|url=http://archive.boston.com/business/articles/2004/03/14/david_platt_wants_to_cure_cancer_can_his_company_avoid_life_support/|work=Boston Globe|date=March 14, 2004}}</ref>  He joined the company as Chief Scientific Officer in 2006.<ref name=PPpressrelease2006/>  Pro-Pharmaceuticals named a new CEO in March 2011,<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Release: Pro-Pharmaceuticals Names Peter G. Traber, M.D., Former Glaxosmithkline Chief Medical Officer & President Emeritus Of Baylor College Of Medicine, President & Chief Executive Officer (Nasdaq:Galt)|url=http://investor.galectintherapeutics.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=811609|publisher=Galectin Therapeutics|date=March 9, 2011}}</ref> and gave Klyosov a one-year contract to continue as CSO the same month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Form 8-K, Exhibit Exhibit 10.1: Amended Employment Agreement dated 03/31/2011 between the Co.and Anatole Klyosov|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1133416/000119312511090230/dex101.htm|publisher=SEC Edgar|date=April 6, 2011}} See [https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1133416/000119312511090230/0001193125-11-090230-index.htm 8-K index page]</ref>  The company was renamed as Galectin Therapeutics in May 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lang|first1=Michelle|title=Pro-Pharmaceuticals renames to Galectin Therapeutics|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/blog/mass-high-tech/2011/05/pro-pharmaceuticals-renames-to-galectin.html|work=Boston Business Journal|date=May 26, 2011}}</ref> He then became a member of the company's scientific advisory board.<ref name=GalectinBIo/>\n\nFrom 2008<ref>{{cite web | last = Lebedev | first = V. P. | author-link = :ru:\u041b\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432, \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 |date= 2013-02-03 |title= \u041f\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0440\u044f\u044e\u0442 \u043c\u0438\u0440 (\u0421\u0442\u0435\u0431 \u0417\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0430 \u041a\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430)|trans-title= Protoslavs on Elephants Conquer the World (Zadornov's Banter and Klyosov's Science) |url= http://lebed.com/2013/art6160.htm |language= ru  |publisher= [[:ru:\u041b\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044c (\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0445)|Lebed (almanac)]] |access-date= 2017-01-09 |quote= \u0428\u0435\u043b 2008 \u0433, \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e \u043a\u0430\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\u044b \u041a\u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0441 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e \u0414\u041d\u041a-\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u044e = It was 2008, the beginning of Klyosov's career with his science about DNA-genealogy.}}</ref> Klyosov is also known as the author of what he calls \"DNA genealogy\" and \"new science\", aimed to synthesize [[biology]], [[anthropology]], [[archaeology]] and [[linguistics]] and to implement methods of [[chemical kinetics]] in [[genetics]].<ref name=l24/><ref name=bal2>{{cite web |last= Balanovsky|first= O. P.|date= |title= Y-\u0445\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0441\u043e\u043c\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0442\u044e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u044f\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0443\u043b\u044f\u0446\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0438 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0438: \u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0438 \u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0445\u043e\u0434\u044b |trans-title= Y-chromosome as a tool for the reconstruction of the origin of the Turkic-speaking populations of the Caucasus and Eurasia: scientific and unscientific approaches (presentation at the conference \"Ethnogenesis, history, language and culture of Karachai-Balkar people\", 29 Nov 2014) |url= http://antropogenez.ru/review/812/ |language= ru  |publisher= antropogenez.ru |access-date= 2017-01-08}}</ref> Klyosov described his \"DNA genealogy\" as a \"patriotic science\" and between 2010 and 2016 published 10 books in this field.<ref name=ForPol2016/> In some of his writings Klyosov tried to refute the [[Out of Africa hypothesis]] and proposed his alternative Into Africa theory<ref name=\"ucl\">{{cite web |title= Problematical theories |url= https://www.ucl.ac.uk/mace-lab/debunking/theories |publisher= [[University College London|UCL]], Molecular and Cultural Evolution Lab |accessdate= 2016-10-22}}</ref> with \"outlandish claims\" that the human species originated in Northern Russia.<ref name=l24/><ref name=ForPol2016>{{cite news |last1= Antonova |first1= Maria |title=Putin\u2019s Great Patriotic Pseudoscience |url= https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/11/29/putins-great-patriotic-pseudoscience/ |work= Foreign Policy |date=November 29, 2016}}</ref> According to scientists from various fields, \"DNA genealogy\" is [[pseudoscience]],<ref name=bal>{{cite book |last= Balanovsky|first= O. P.|date= |chapter= \u041b\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 |trans-chapter= Pseudoscientific discussions |title= \u0413\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0434 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u044b|trans-title= Gene pool of Europe |url= http://xn--c1acc6aafa1c.xn--p1ai/?page_id=5166 |language= ru |location= |publisher= KMK Scientific Press |year= 2015 |pages=64\u201366 |isbn=9785990715707}}</ref> and they have characterized it as \"DNA demagoguery\u201d.<ref name=l24>{{cite web | last1 = Balanovskaya | first1 = E. V. | author-link1 = | last2 = Borinskaya| first2 = S. A. | author-link2 = | last3 = Buzhilova| first3 = A. P.| author-link3 = | last4 = Volkov| first4 = V. G.| author-link4 = | last5 = Gerasimova| first5 = M. M.| author-link5 = | last6 = Godina| first6 = E. Z.| author-link6 = | last7 = Dubova| first7 = N. A.| author-link7 = | last8 = Dybo| first8 = A. V.| author-link8 = Anna Vladimirovna Dybo| last9 = Episkoposyan| first9 = L. M.| author-l